{"author":{"id":"68dfa65ee618df2786e7da658bbfbbcc1f0c757170d9426e314e5f0886bcc55d"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1705566733,"nonce":"s/PwI3pfBnNzb30iz0eeHkDhg7o=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDOAW4Y0s5xIXjf","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/5703#issuecomment-1898019039"},"message":"The tool wrapper is not responsible for naming collection elements. It just gets two datasets inputs and outputs 4 dataset outputs. Then Galaxy assigns this to the output collections, i.e. Galaxy maps the tool over the input collections. Without help Galaxy can't know from which of the two input collections the output collections should get their names. \n\nSo I guess this should be fixed by setting `default_identifier_source` for the outputs (or refrain from using unpaired collection inputs/outputs for paired data). Didn't know about this one yet :) \n\nI think we should generalize this issue since there seem to be a few tools that have this problem (`grep \"\u003cdata\" tools -r | grep R1` or grep \"\u003cdata\" tools -r | grep forward` .. but this will contain some false positives) . Maybe `default_identifier_source` could be covered better in the docs somewhere?\n\nFor the example I was wondering if the two inputs are supposed to be paired? But I guess this was just for demonstrating the issue.","files":null},{"type":6,"timestamp":1705574228,"nonce":"FNkru/8mCwBskwQwyrKdv03GZVU=","metadata":{"github-id":"UCE_lALOAW4Y0s5xIXjfzj5Xidc"},"target":"0dcb433b34c7dfd1c97b2aecadbdc36fb95290514deebc12901858fbe2aabdeb","message":"The tool wrapper is not responsible for naming collection elements. It just gets two datasets inputs and outputs 4 dataset outputs. Then Galaxy assigns this to the output collections, i.e. Galaxy maps the tool over the input collections. Without help Galaxy can't know from which of the two input collections the output collections should get their names. \n\nSo I guess this should be fixed by setting `default_identifier_source` for the outputs (or refrain from using unpaired collection inputs/outputs for paired data). Didn't know about this one yet :) \n\nI think we should generalize this issue since there seem to be a few tools that have this problem (`grep \"\u003cdata\" tools -r | grep R1` or grep `\u003cdata\" tools -r | grep forward` .. but this will contain some false positives) . Maybe `default_identifier_source` could be covered better in the docs somewhere?\n\nFor the example I was wondering if the two inputs are supposed to be paired? But I guess this was just for demonstrating the issue.","files":null}]}